  "stem": "<p>The polynomial function <i>p</i> has values <i>p</i>(&minus;3) = 0, <i>p</i>(&minus;1) = 0, and <i>p</i>(2) = 0. Based on these values, which of the following must be a factor of <i>p</i>?</p>",
  "answerOptions": [
    {
      "id": "a",
      "content": "<p>(<i>x</i> &minus; 3)</p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "b",
      "content": "<p>(<i>x</i> + 1)(<i>x</i> &minus; 2)</p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "c",
      "content": "<p>(<i>x</i> &minus; 1)(<i>x</i> + 2)</p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "d",
      "content": "<p>(<i>x</i> + 3)(<i>x</i> + 1)(<i>x</i> &minus; 2)</p>"
    }
  ],
  "keys": [
    "d"
  ],
  "rationale": "<p>Choice D is correct. By the factor theorem, if <i>p</i>(<i>c</i>) = 0 then (<i>x</i> &minus; <i>c</i>) is a factor of <i>p</i>. Since <i>p</i>(&minus;3) = 0, <i>p</i>(&minus;1) = 0, and <i>p</i>(2) = 0, the factors (<i>x</i> + 3), (<i>x</i> + 1), and (<i>x</i> &minus; 2) must all divide <i>p</i>. The product (<i>x</i> + 3)(<i>x</i> + 1)(<i>x</i> &minus; 2) is therefore a factor.</p>",
